<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title>World News, Today World News, Latest International News, World Breaking News, Trending News of World - Times of India</title><link>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world</link><description>World News Today: Read the latest world news headlines, Current International breaking news world wide. In depth analysis and top news headlines world wide.</description><language>en-gb</language><lastBuildDate>2026-07-06T21:52:15+05:30</lastBuildDate><atom:link type="application/rss+xml" rel="self" href="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/rssfeeds/296589292.cms"/><copyright>Copyright:(C) Mon, 06 Jul 2026 21:52:15 IST Bennett Coleman &amp; Co. Ltd, http://in.indiatimes.com/policyterms/1554651.cms</copyright><docs>http://syndication.indiatimes.com/</docs><image><title>World News, Today World News, Latest International News, World Breaking News, Trending News of World - Times of India</title><url>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/507610.cms</url><link>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world</link></image><item><title><![CDATA[300,000-year-old Homo naledi fossils from a South African cave suggest the ancient human relative may have been a female-only species, new study reveals]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132220531.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[A recent examination of ancient dental remains from South Africa's cave systems has led to a striking conclusion. Proteomic analysis revealed solely female protein markers in the samples examined. This intriguing finding implies that all identified Homo naledi individuals could potentially be female. Researchers are currently delving into possible explanations for this unexpected trend, which raises significant questions regarding established beliefs about the species' gender distribution.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/300000-year-old-homo-naledi-fossils-from-a-south-african-cave-suggest-the-ancient-human-relative-may-have-been-a-female-only-species-new-study-reveals/articleshow/132220531.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/science/300000-year-old-homo-naledi-fossils-from-a-south-african-cave-suggest-the-ancient-human-relative-may-have-been-a-female-only-species-new-study-reveals/articleshow/132220531.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-06T21:47:13+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">TOI Science Desk</dc:creator><enclosure type="image/jpeg" url="https://static.toiimg.com/photo/msid-132221019,imgsize-149532.cms"/></item><item><title><![CDATA[“I don’t fear these…”: Candace Owens reignites Erika Kirk feud during Tyler Robinson hearing in Charlie Kirk case]]></title><description>&lt;img border="0" hspace="10" align="left" style="margin-top:3px;margin-right:5px;" src="https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/photo/132220670.cms" /&gt;<![CDATA[Candace Owens reacted strongly as Tyler Robinson’s preliminary hearing began on July 6. She called the proceedings a “show trial,” questioned how evidence is being handled and criticized the court process. In a second post, she shared a faith-based message dedicated to Charlie Kirk. The hearing will determine whether prosecutors have enough evidence to move the case to trial.]]></description><link><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/i-dont-fear-these-candace-owens-reignites-erika-kirk-feud-during-tyler-robinson-hearing-in-charlie-kirk-case/articleshow/132220670.cms]]></link><guid><![CDATA[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us-streamers/i-dont-fear-these-candace-owens-reignites-erika-kirk-feud-during-tyler-robinson-hearing-in-charlie-kirk-case/articleshow/132220670.cms]]></guid><pubDate>2026-07-06T21:19:46+05:30</pubDate><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Sumit Roy</dc:creator><enclo